05904nam a22006975i 9780300157659DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221995ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001576597 a10.12987/97803001576592doi  a(DE-B1597)625753  a(OCoLC)1322125873  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aSOC0130002bisacsh04a305.26/0973222/eng1 aBass, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOlder and Active :bHow Americans over 55 Are Contributing to Society /cScott Bass. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©1995  a1 online resource :b16 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Older and Active -- t2 Health and the Employment Capability of Older Americans -- t3 Older Americans As Workers -- t4 Increasing Volunteering among Older People -- t5 Older Caregivers and the Future of Informal Caregiving -- t6 Patterns of Support Given by Older Americans to Their Children -- t7 The Value of Productive Activities of Older Americans -- t8 Dimensions of Productive Engagement -- t9 Training and Education of Older Americans As Workers and Volunteers -- t10 Social Integration, Participation, and Exchange in Five Industrial Countries -- t11 Toward Pro-Work Policies and Programs for Older Americans -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOlder people in the United States are living longer, staying healthier, and leaving the labor force earlier than ever before. They have leisure time and are willing, able, and qualified to be productive members of society. This book focuses on the contributions that many older people can and do make and the policy changes that are necessary to harness this productive capacity—for the good of the country and for the good of the individuals involved. The contributors to this book—experts in economics, sociology, political science, social welfare, and policy studies—have drawn on new data from a survey of 2,999 Americans aged 55 and older conducted by Louis Harris Associates for The Commonwealth Fund. One chapter also analyzes results from a cross-national survey of 900 people aged 65 and older in the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom, West Germany, and Japan. According to the findings, three out of four older Americans are actively engaged in working for pay, volunteering for organizations, caring for sick or disabled relatives or friends, or helping their children or grandchildren. Many are involved in several of these activities. The book thus corrects the stereotypes of seniors as affluent retirees or frail dependents, providing a more accurate description of older people's interests and activities. It also assesses the economic value of their productivity and recommends ways to facilitate their involvement in the work force.Copublished with The Commonwealth Fund  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBarth, Michael C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBass, Scott A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkhauser, Richard V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaro, Francis G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Kevin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoty, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEggebeen, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcnaught, William, econtributor.4ctb4https